The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Sports | Briefs
                                                                                                                       7                                                                                                        
	Leeds: Reigning champion Pankaj Advani remained on course for the second successive World Professional Billiards title after securing contrasting wins over compatriot Sushrat Pandia and Englands Martin Goodwill on the opening day of the event here. Five-time winner Geet Sethi, making his 19th appearance at the event, scored an emphatic 781-397 win over teammate Siddharth Parikh before humbling Englands Bem French 1223186 at the Northern Snooker Centre.        
	London: Bolton Wanderers striker Ivan Klasnic has been arrested on suspicion of rape, according to media reports. The club has so far not commented about the allegation. as arrested some time later.         
	Montpellier: Mahesh Bhupathi and Max Mirnyi squandered three match points in the super tie-break to crash out of Open Sud de France, losing a tightly contested match to Ross Hutchins and Stephen Huss, here, on Thursday. The top seeded Indo-Belarusian pair lost 6-3, 3-6, 12-14 to the unseeded British-Australian pair.        
	New Delhi: P. Kashyap and Anand Pawar beat Scott Evans of Ireland and Hans-Kristian Vittinghus, respectively, to sail into the second round, in the Denmark Open Super Series at Odense, in Denmark. Chetan Anand, however, crashed out of the mens singles event after losing to eighth seed Hu Yun of Hong Kong 21-15, 15-21, 16-2.        
	Bhopal: Sushil Kumar has been appointed chief coach-cum-technical advisor of the Madhya Pradesh Wrestling Academy. This will be Sushils first stint in coaching.        
	Melbourne: As Indian investors wait in the wings to buy stakes in Australian domestic sides, Australian Cricketers Association (ACA) Thursday backed the idea, saying it would not just bring in money but also raise the profile of the sport Down Under.      
	 New Delhi: The Supreme Court has adjourned till November 11 the hearing on former IPL commissioner Lalit Modi rsquo;s petition challenging the composition of the disciplinary committee probing charges of financial irregularities against him. The court was informed that efforts for a patch up between Modi and the BCCI have failed. Ram Jethmalani, appearing for Modi, told the court that attempts for a settlement, despite the best efforts, did not succeed.
        
	Calcutta: Bengal grabbed three points by virtue of a first innings lead, in a CK Nayudu Trophy (under-22) match, against Orissa. The match ended in a draw on Thursday as Orissa were 330 for three in their second innings. Girija Raut and Biplab Samantray slammed centuries for Orissa.      
	Bengal 481/6. Orissa 239 amp; 330/3 (Girija Rout 152 not out, Biplab Samantray 116, Alok Sharma 62/2). Match drawn.                                                                                                                                                      
